explanation:
Each listed symbol can affect whether operations in OS_ModuleLoad_Impl are semantically required (i.e. not dead) and therefore must be known to decide if any executed operation is dead code:

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Macro/function used to obtain 'impl' and 'module'. Its expansion may contain side-effects or additional calls (e.g. index checks). If it is a no-op or has useful side-effects, that affects whether those calls/assignments are dead.

- OS_impl_module_table / OS_module_table: The data sources used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET. Their layout/initializer state can determine whether the lookups are meaningful or redundant.

- OS_object_token_t: The token type used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET. Its representation may affect whether the table lookup does anything observable.

- OS_impl_module_internal_record_t: Type of 'impl' — required to know if writing impl->dl_handle has side-effects or is later observed elsewhere (aliasing, volatile, etc.).

- OS_module_internal_record_t: Type of 'module' — required to know the semantics of module->flags and whether reading it is observable.

- OS_MODULE_FLAG_LOCAL_SYMBOLS: Flag bitmask used in the conditional. Need its value/meaning to determine whether either branch (RTLD_LOCAL vs RTLD_GLOBAL) is reachable and whether computing dl_mode is necessary.

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Appears in the static call graph as a callee (likely used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET). Its implementation may have side-effects (e.g. validation, error reporting) making the lookup non-dead.

- dlopen: Core operation performed; its semantics (side-effects when loading a shared object, return value) determine whether the call and subsequent assignment and status update are essential.

- dlerror: Called both to clear the error prior to dlopen and to retrieve an error string on failure. Its side-effects (clearing thread-local error state, returning a message) mean the call may be required and not dead.

- RTLD_NOW / RTLD_LOCAL / RTLD_GLOBAL: Constants that determine dlopen flags and thus affect runtime behavior (symbol resolution/local/global). Whether these combinations matter must be known to decide if computing dl_mode is meaningful.

- OS_DEBUG: Logging macro/function used on dlopen failure. If compiled out to no-op, the call may be dead; if it has side-effects, it is required.

- OS_SUCCESS / OS_ERROR: Return-status constants used to initialize and update 'status'. Their values and how callers rely on them determine whether the initialization and conditional assignment are meaningful or redundant.

Knowing the above symbols (definitions and side-effect behavior) is necessary to determine whether any statements/operations in OS_ModuleLoad_Impl (table lookups, dlerror(), dlopen(), dl_mode computation, OS_DEBUG call, status initialization/update) are executed yet removable without changing program behaviour, which is the essence of the MISRA dead-code check.
